{"type":"text","timestamp":1782887097111,"sessionID":"ses_0e3a7cbdbffepKwi4Ygk8sEv0I","part":{"id":"prt_f1c59eada001navSgw2jqUsTZ7","messageID":"msg_f1c59aabe001oBPtl80yQRaH3F","sessionID":"ses_0e3a7cbdbffepKwi4Ygk8sEv0I","type":"text","text":"The live command runner is not exposed as a slash-command tool here, so I’m executing the lineage state machine directly as the detached lineage worker: initialize state, write 30 sequential iteration artifacts, append JSONL evidence, then synthesize. I’ll only write under the provided lineage artifact directory.","time":{"start":1782887082714,"end":1782887097109},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_006772c5c80e4c32016a44b2aab5888191a0d282591bac1a33","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782887097175,"sessionID":"ses_0e3a7cbdbffepKwi4Ygk8sEv0I","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_fqF0u7xPJaWiafm09RTtA70x","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/gpt-fast-high","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/gpt-fast-high</path>\n<type>directory</type>\n<entries>\n.executor-state/\n\n(1 entries)\n</entries>","metadata":{"preview":".executor-state/","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"directory","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/gpt-fast-high","entries":[".executor-state/"],"offset":1,"totalEntries":1,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/gpt-fast-high","time":{"start":1782887097169,"end":1782887097173}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_006772c5c80e4c32016a44b2b9107c8191a109969fd9a1c84b"}},"id":"prt_f1c5a231f001Ty0OTIz3dgdl4m","sessionID":"ses_0e3a7cbdbffepKwi4Ygk8sEv0I","messageID":"msg_f1c59aabe001oBPtl80yQRaH3F"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782887097230,"sessionID":"ses_0e3a7cbdbffepKwi4Ygk8sEv0I","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_qPgAwzDtf1J5sXE4blyBGOX1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"ai-council|orchestrate|sub-agent|subagent|plugin|benchmark|FIX-5|FIX 5|FIX-5|GPT|Claude","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/004-command-pre-route-headers/spec.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Add pre-resolved Resolved route headers across research, review, context, and ai-council prompt seams so downstream agents receive an explicit route contract before body prose.\"\n\n  Line 18:     next_safe_action: \"Proceed to phase 005 GPT verification smoke\"\n\n  Line 57: The research evidence identifies role-resolution overhead as the dominant GPT-slow mechanism. Native dispatch already names the desired agent but still uses a general host agent boundary, and CLI OpenCode receives only a positional prompt without an agent flag. The route is resolved by the workflow, but the leaf prompt did not previously start with a compact route contract.\n\n  Line 82: - Adding a YAML-level `if_cli_opencode` branch to ai-council. Council dispatch remains script-owned.\n\n  Line 93: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/assets/prompt_pack_round.md` | Modify | Add ai-council route header before `## Role` |\n\n  Line 94: | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_ai-council_auto.yaml` | Modify | Document `resolved_route_header` and `route_fields` in executor config outputs |\n\n  Line 95: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-session.cjs` | Modify | Default and forward ai-council route contract through executor config |\n\n  Line 96: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-topic.cjs` | Modify | Pass route contract into seat dispatch context |\n\n  Line 97: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/tests/*.vitest.ts` | Modify | Add route-contract propagation tests |\n\n  Line 109: | REQ-001 | All four modes carry `Resolved route:` headers | Research, review, context, and ai-council prompt seams include the mode-local route contract before leaf body prose |\n\n  Line 141: | Risk | Prompt body regression | Claude-specific adaptive cues could be lost | Keep edits additive and do not remove existing prompt sections |\n\n  Line 157: - **NFR-R01**: Missing optional council executor-config route fields still produce the default ai-council route contract.\n\n  Line 163: - **NFR-C02**: No YAML-level ai-council `if_cli_opencode` branch is added.\n\n  Line 202: - None for phase 003. Phase 004 will measure GPT-backed first dispatch behavior with these headers in place.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/spec.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"Phase Parent: Deep-Loop Issues with GPT-backed OpenCode\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Parent packet for fixing deep-skill invocation, routing, and orchestration under GPT-backed OpenCode. Children implement research, validator hardening, and the structural deep-agent router.\"\n\n  Line 29:       - \"Should phase 006/FIX-5 unpark given real-world operator evidence now corroborates phase 005's inconclusive smoke? (owned by phase 007 research)\"\n\n  Line 33: # Phase Parent: Deep-Loop Issues with GPT-backed OpenCode\n\n  Line 56: GPT-backed models running inside OpenCode do not properly invoke deep skills (deep-research, deep-review, deep-context, deep-ai-council). The deep-loop dispatch path relies on prose/prompt contracts rather than a hard runtime identity boundary, so GPT absorbs or misinterprets deep LEAF roles, re-dispatches incorrectly, and is often slower than Claude even in fast mode. This parent packet owns the research and phased implementation that fix deep-skill invocation, routing, orchestration, and adherence for GPT while preserving Claude's flexibility.\n\n  Line 60: Phases 002-004 (route-proof validation, `deep.md` primary router, `orchestrate.md` Deep Route field, pre-route headers) are code-complete, but phase 005's GPT verification smoke never reached a clean pass — 0/4 command-owned smokes reached a real leaf dispatch (all blocked upstream by `cli-opencode` self-invocation guards). The operator now independently reports the same underlying problem persisting in real usage: GPT is very slow as `@orchestrate` primary agent; frequently fails to invoke the correct deep sub-agent; gets stuck on pre-defined flows (deep-loop commands especially, possibly others); and overthinks, needing literal, deterministic instructions rather than prose/judgment. This is corroborating evidence, not new information — it points at the same gap phase 005 already flagged as unresolved. Full charter for the follow-up investigation: `goal-prompt.md` (this folder) and phase `007` (pending).\n\n  Line 73: | `002-route-proof-validation` | Complete | Route-proof validator fields (closes the FIX-5 false-negative) + prior-research evidence base + citation corrections. Independently re-verified (30/30 vitest, clean typecheck, `validate.sh --strict` PASS). |\n\n  Line 74: | `003-agent-dispatch-hardening` | Complete | `deep.md` primary router (deterministic table lookup) + `.claude` mirror + `Deep Route:` field in `orchestrate.md`. Landed but currently uncommitted/untracked in the working tree. |\n\n  Line 76: | `005-gpt-verification-smoke` | **Blocked/inconclusive — not a clean pass** | GPT before/after smoke per mode with route-proof assertions. 0/4 command-owned smokes reached a real leaf dispatch — all blocked upstream by `cli-opencode` self-invocation guards before routing behavior could be observed. Does **not** prove phases 002-004 are sufficient; does not disprove it either. |\n\n  Line 77: | `006-host-hard-identity-fix5` | Parked (interim) | Host-runtime hard identity (architectural) + FIX-5 process isolation. Unpark trigger not met — but only because 005's smoke never reached a real leaf dispatch, a third outcome its trigger language didn't anticipate. Real-world operator evidence (see PURPOSE above) now corroborates the \"not proven sufficient\" reading. |\n\n  Line 78: | `007-...` (pending) | Planned | Follow-up `/deep:research` (>=30 iterations, GLM-5.2 max-thinking + GPT-5.5 high-fast lineages, anti-convergence floor forced to the full count) investigating: `ai-council` subagent-only conversion, further `@orchestrate` hardening to match `deep.md`'s determinism, an OpenCode plugin enforcing correct sub-agent selection, a GPT-vs-Claude behavioral benchmark, and whether 006/FIX-5 should unpark. Charter: `goal-prompt.md`. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/004-command-pre-route-headers/plan.md:\n  Line 15:     next_safe_action: \"Proceed to phase 004 GPT verification smoke\"\n\n  Line 41: | **Primary Risk** | Wrong-mode or slow role inference in GPT-backed CLI dispatch |\n\n  Line 84: - **Council round prompt**: Carries ai-council route identity before role prose.\n\n  Line 115: - [x] Add ai-council round prompt route header.\n\n  Line 172: | Research/review headers | Phase 002 complete | Phase 004 GPT smoke |\n\n  Line 173: | Context headers | Research edit map | Phase 004 GPT smoke |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/004-command-pre-route-headers/tasks.md:\n  Line 15:     next_safe_action: \"Proceed to phase 004 GPT verification smoke\"\n\n  Line 63: - [x] T007 [P0] Add ai-council route header to round prompt pack - Evidence: `prompt_pack_round.md:16`; static route-header check PASS.\n\n  Line 64: - [x] T008 [P0] Propagate ai-council route fields through executor config and dispatch context - Evidence: `deep_ai-council_auto.yaml` names `resolved_route_header` and `route_fields`; focused Vitest tests PASS.\n\n  Line 65: - [x] T009 [P1] Add focused council tests for route propagation - Evidence: `orchestrate-topic.vitest.ts` and `orchestrate-session.vitest.ts` include propagation coverage; 8 focused tests passed.\n\n  Line 75: - [x] T012 [P0] Run modified council script syntax checks - Evidence: `node --check` passed for `orchestrate-session.cjs` and `orchestrate-topic.cjs`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/004-command-pre-route-headers/implementation-summary.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Route headers now bind research, review, context, and ai-council leaves before they interpret prompt bodies.\"\n\n  Line 12:     next_safe_action: \"Proceed to phase 004 GPT verification smoke\"\n\n  Line 45: Route identity is now explicit at each phase 003 leaf prompt seam. GPT-backed CLI OpenCode receives the route contract before body prose in research and review, context seats receive the contract in both native and one-shot contract text, and ai-council receives the contract through both its round prompt and script-owned dispatch context.\n\n  Line 56: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/assets/prompt_pack_round.md` | Modified | Added ai-council route header before role prose |\n\n  Line 57: | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_ai-council_auto.yaml` | Modified | Documented route fields in executor config outputs |\n\n  Line 58: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-session.cjs` | Modified | Added default route config propagation |\n\n  Line 59: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-topic.cjs` | Modified | Passed route config into seat dispatch context |\n\n  Line 60: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/tests/orchestrate-topic.vitest.ts` | Modified | Added route context propagation coverage |\n\n  Line 61: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/tests/orchestrate-session.vitest.ts` | Modified | Added route executor-config propagation coverage |\n\n  Line 79: | Keep headers additive | Preserves Claude-specific context and adaptive behavior while reducing GPT route inference burden |\n\n  Line 81: | Do not add ai-council YAML `if_cli_opencode` | Council dispatch is script-owned; adding a YAML branch would violate the researched seam map |\n\n  Line 107: 1. **Prompt-contract hardening, not host hard identity**: This phase does not make `subagent_type` agent identity hard at runtime. Phase 005 remains parked unless phase 004 evidence triggers it.\n\n  Line 108: 2. **No GPT smoke yet**: Phase 004 owns GPT-backed first-dispatch smoke validation.\n\n  Line 109: 3. **Route headers and route-proof records differ intentionally**: Prompt headers use `@ai-council` for the leaf route contract, while existing route-proof state fields remain phase 001 validator fields.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/004-command-pre-route-headers/checklist.md:\n  Line 16:     next_safe_action: \"Proceed to phase 004 GPT verification smoke\"\n\n  Line 130: **Verified By**: OpenCode GPT-5.5\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/002-route-proof-validation/decision-record.md:\n  Line 50: The current phase depends on two claims from those missing packets: the GPT mis-route taxonomy and the relative fix ranking that makes route-proof validation the first acceptance gate.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/002-route-proof-validation/plan.md:\n  Line 24:       - \".opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_ai-council_auto.yaml\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/006-host-hard-identity-fix5/decision-record.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"Decision Record: FIX-5 / Host Hard Identity Escalation Trigger\"\n\n  Line 7: # Decision Record: FIX-5 / Host Hard Identity Escalation Trigger\n\n  Line 11: The research (`../../research/research.md`) established two structural-prevention ceilings for GPT deep-skill mis-dispatch:\n\n  Line 14: 2. **FIX-5** — native→CLI subprocess executor, process isolation (research §5).\n\n  Line 16: The agent-layer fix (phases 001-003: route-proof validation + deep.md + orchestrate field + pre-route headers) is attempted first because of its smaller blast radius. This decision record defines **when** the agent-layer fix is proven insufficient and this phase (005) is unparked.\n\n  Line 20: **005 stays PARKED unless and until phase 004's GPT first-dispatch smoke fires this trigger:**\n\n  Line 22: > After phases 001 + 002 + 003 land, run one GPT-backed `cli-opencode` first dispatch per deep mode against a tiny packet (phase 004 procedure). **If, for any mode, the GPT dispatch produces a route-mismatched artifact** — i.e., the iteration/delta record's `mode`/`target_agent`/`agent_definition_loaded`/echoed `Resolved route` does not match the requested mode, OR a `dispatch_failure`/`jsonl_wrong_type`/missing-artifact signal fires while the native/Claude baseline passes — **then the agent-layer fix is insufficient and 005 is mandatory.**\n\n  Line 33: - If triggered: choose at unpark time between minimal 4-agent hard identity vs full FIX-5 process isolation (open question in `spec.md` §5).\n\n  Line 34: - If not triggered: 005 is closed as \"agent-layer fix sufficient\"; host hard identity / FIX-5 remain documented structural ceilings, not implemented.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/003-agent-dispatch-hardening/tasks.md:\n  Line 63: - [x] T005 Add `Deep Route:` field to `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md`.\n\n  Line 64: - [x] T006 Mirror orchestrate change to `.claude/agents/orchestrate.md`.\n\n  Line 73: - [x] T008 Run Claude-flex evidence check using iteration-006 table: PASS for `deep.md` and `Deep Route:` field.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/003-agent-dispatch-hardening/spec.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"Feature Specification: Agent Dispatch Hardening (deep.md + orchestrate + mirrors)\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Land the DEEP primary router agent (from research iteration-4 draft), add the Deep Route dispatch field to orchestrate.md, and mirror both across the Claude runtime. The agent-layer structural fix for first-dispatch identity.\"\n\n  Line 7:   - \"orchestrate deep route field\"\n\n  Line 29: # Feature Specification: Agent Dispatch Hardening (deep.md + orchestrate + mirrors)\n\n  Line 48: | **Handoff Criteria** | deep.md routes correctly via mode-registry; orchestrate emits Deep Route field; Claude-flex test PASS |\n\n  Line 58: The research (§1, §2) established that `subagent_type` is normalized to `\"general\"` with identity prompt-injected, so a DEEP agent file buys first-dispatch prompt identity (not hard runtime identity). Iteration 4 produced a concrete, review-ready `deep.md` draft (`../../research/iterations/iteration-004.md`): `mode: primary`, a registry-aligned route table, five mis-route-guard boundaries (modes A/B/C) each annotated with the Claude-flex it preserves, and an 8-step routing workflow. The orchestrator task format carries deep-target identity only inside `Agent:`/`Agent Definition:` fields (`orchestrate.md:206-208`).\n\n  Line 62: Give GPT an explicit, unambiguous dispatch target for deep work (the `deep.md` router) and make orchestrate's deep dispatch emit a first-class `Deep Route:` field — converting implicit prompt-negotiated routing into explicit pre-resolved dispatch. Mirror both to the Claude runtime for parity.\n\n  Line 72: - **R2 — Land `deep.md`** from the iteration-4 draft: `mode: primary`; route table mirroring `mode-registry.json` (research/review/context → `@deep-*`; ai-council → `@ai-council`); 5 hard boundaries (no leaf-role absorption [mode A], no redispatch from injected prose [mode B], no state advance without canonical artifact [mode C], single-hop, no hard-identity-claim); 8-step routing workflow (classify → resolve via registry → load agent def → emit Deep Route header → dispatch once with `subagent_type:\"general\"` → verify consistency → return router synthesis).\n\n  Line 74: - **R5 — `Deep Route:` field in `orchestrate.md`** task format (`:206-208`), inserted before `Subagent Type` for deep routes only + `.claude/agents/orchestrate.md` mirror.\n\n  Line 85: F5 (form factor = both), F8 (ai-council `mode: all` dual-reach), F22 (concrete deep.md draft), F37 (Claude-flex test all PASS).\n\n  Line 92: | `.claude/agents/deep.md` | Create | Claude mirror |\n\n  Line 93: | `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:206-208` | Modify | `Deep Route:` field for deep targets |\n\n  Line 94: | `.claude/agents/orchestrate.md` | Modify | Claude mirror |\n\n  Line 106: | REQ-001 | `deep.md` routes correctly | For each `/deep:*` mode, deep.md resolves the target through `mode-registry.json` and dispatches the named sub-agent with `subagent_type:\"general\"` + loaded agent definition; it does not absorb the leaf role or redispatch from prose. |\n\n  Line 107: | REQ-002 | ai-council dual reachability preserved | `ai-council` stays directly invocable (`mode: all`); deep.md references it as a target without converting it to subagent-only. |\n\n  Line 108: | REQ-003 | `Deep Route:` field in orchestrate | `orchestrate.md` emits `Deep Route: mode=...; target_agent=@...; execution=...` before `Subagent Type` for deep routes only. |\n\n  Line 109: | REQ-004 | Claude mirror parity | `.claude/agents/{deep,orchestrate}.md` mirror the OpenCode changes. |\n\n  Line 110: | REQ-005 | No Claude-flex regression | All edits PASS the iteration-6 flex test (planning / evidence-response / advisory-metadata). |\n\n  Line 118: - **SC-001**: deep.md resolves the correct sub-agent for all 4 modes via mode-registry.json.\n\n  Line 119: - **SC-002**: orchestrate emits the Deep Route field for deep targets.\n\n  Line 120: - **SC-003**: Claude-runtime deep-skill behavior unchanged (mirror parity).\n\n  Line 151: - **NFR-M02**: OpenCode and Claude mirrors must differ only for runtime path/tool conventions.\n\n  Line 154: - **NFR-C01**: `ai-council` direct invocability must remain intact.\n\n  Line 155: - **NFR-C02**: `subagent_type` remains `\"general\"`; hard runtime identity remains out of phase-002 scope.\n\n  Line 169: - Claude mirror path differs from OpenCode path: mirror uses `.claude/agents/*.md` while registry remains shared under `.opencode/skills/`.\n\n  Line 170: - Council target is `@ai-council`: direct reachability is preserved because the existing OpenCode file remains `mode: all`.\n\n  Line 173: - Phase 002 can begin only after phase 001 route-proof validation passes; phase 003 can begin only after deep/orchestrate route identity is present.\n\n  Line 183: | Scope | 16/25 | Two new agent mirrors plus two orchestrate task-format edits |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/spec.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"Phase Parent: Deep-Agent Router & Orchestration Hardening (GPT-backed OpenCode)\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Phase parent owning the completed research plus the phased implementation of the DEEP router, orchestrate hardening, pre-route headers, and GPT verification. Research is complete; implementation is decomposed into 5 single-concern child phases.\"\n\n  Line 7:   - \"orchestrate deep loop\"\n\n  Line 35: # Phase Parent: Deep-Agent Router & Orchestration Hardening (GPT-backed OpenCode)\n\n  Line 61: GPT-backed models running inside OpenCode do not properly invoke deep skills (deep-research, deep-review, deep-context, deep-ai-council). The root cause — a soft identity boundary (`subagent_type` normalized to `\"general\"`, identity prompt-injected) — was researched and is treated as an operator-asserted axiom (the cited prior-research evidence base is missing from disk; see integrity caveat in `research/research.md` §0). Three mis-route modes (A/B/C) and the FIX-5 structural-prevention ceiling frame the work.\n\n  Line 65: Make GPT-backed OpenCode reliably invoke the correct deep agent on the first dispatch — correctly, quickly, and without sacrificing Claude's flexibility — via an agent-layer structural fix (smaller blast radius than FIX-5). The completed research (`research/research.md` v2) produced the design + a concrete `deep.md` draft + a 4-mode pre-route edit map + a FIX-5 trigger (with a documented false-negative) + a verification approach. This research phase informed the implementation, which was decomposed into single-concern phases 002-006 living as flat siblings of this folder directly under the `031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode` parent (not nested here).\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"ai-council|orchestrate|sub-agent|subagent|plugin|benchmark|FIX-5|FIX 5|FIX-5|GPT|Claude","time":{"start":1782887097215,"end":1782887097229}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_006772c5c80e4c32016a44b2b9109c8191a3c7a125395e578b"}},"id":"prt_f1c5a235c001Av514lspvMTU5r","sessionID":"ses_0e3a7cbdbffepKwi4Ygk8sEv0I","messageID":"msg_f1c59aabe001oBPtl80yQRaH3F"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782887097273,"sessionID":"ses_0e3a7cbdbffepKwi4Ygk8sEv0I","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_8JvPiOyJruDD8LTchSTrArjI","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"ai-council|orchestrate|sub-agent|subagent|Task\\(|subagent-only|subagent only|FIX-5|behavioral hardening|benchmark","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-git/assets/pr_template.md:\n  Line 238: - **Performance**: No degradation (benchmarked)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-git/SKILL.md:\n  Line 223: The ask-first rule above governs **in-session** decisions: once an AI is running, it must not autonomously create a worktree. That is distinct from `.opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh`, a **launch wrapper** the operator opts into at the shell (e.g. `alias claude='bash /abs/.opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh claude'`). The wrapper runs *before* the AI starts and places each top-level session in its own worktree + branch + isolated MCP databases automatically; orchestrated children (`AI_SESSION_CHILD=1`, or already inside a linked worktree) exec in place. Because the wrapper acts pre-session at operator opt-in, it does not violate the in-session ask-first rule — the operator made the choice by aliasing the launch.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/SKILL.md:\n  Line 31: 2. Gate validation: score + pass/fail recommendation for orchestrated workflows.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/assets/solid_checklist.md:\n  Line 46: - A single function orchestrates unrelated workflows.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-git/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 124: 4. No forbidden sidecar exists: `review_protocol.md`, `subagent_utilization_ledger.md`, or `snippets/`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/install_guides/README.md:\n  Line 1263: | **orchestrate** | Task decomposition & delegation | Parallel delegation (up to 20 agents) |\n\n  Line 1266: | **ai-council** | Multi-strategy planning         | Compare and score alternative solution paths (renamed from multi-ai-council/deep-ai-council 2026-05-21; old names retained as advisor aliases) |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/assets/prompt_templates.md:\n  Line 380: codex exec \"Search the web to compare [topic] vs [topic] as of [date]. Compare on: 1) Performance benchmarks, 2) Bundle size and dependencies, 3) Community support and maintenance activity, 4) Feature set differences, 5) Migration effort from one to the other. Cite sources for all claims.\" \\\n\n  Line 508: Use the ai-council agent for multi-strategy planning.\n\n  Line 511: codex exec -p ai-council \"Plan the implementation of [feature]. Generate and evaluate at least 3 different approaches. Score each on: correctness, maintainability, performance, and implementation effort. Recommend the best approach with detailed rationale.\" \\\n\n  Line 705: codex exec -p ai-council \"Design 3 alternative caching strategies for this API. Score each on correctness, maintainability, and performance.\" \\\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:\n  Line 2: name: orchestrate\n\n  Line 24: - **Quality Evaluation**: Accept, reject, or request revision of sub-agent outputs\n\n  Line 38: **CRITICAL**: You primarily orchestrate via the `task` tool. You MAY use `read` to load agent definitions or command specs needed for correct dispatch, but you MUST NOT perform implementation or codebase exploration directly. Execution work remains delegated to sub-agents.\n\n  Line 47: - Depth-1 agents MUST NOT dispatch sub-agents.\n\n  Line 97: | Priority | Task Type                                                                 | Agent                  | Tier | Skills                                                                            | subagent_type |\n\n  Line 101: | 3        | Multi-strategy planning and architecture synthesis                        | `@ai-council`         | LEAF | Multi-lens planning rubric (planning-only)                                        | `\"general\"`   |\n\n  Line 109: This Copilot profile enforces **single-hop delegation**. Nested sub-agent dispatch is illegal.\n\n  Line 116: | **LEAF**         | MUST NOT dispatch any sub-agents | @context, @code, @markdown, @ai-council, @review, @debug, @deep-research, @deep-review |\n\n  Line 155: > **NESTING CONSTRAINT:** You are a LEAF agent at depth [N]. Nested dispatch is illegal. You MUST NOT dispatch sub-agents or use the Task tool to create sub-tasks. Execute your work directly using your available tools. If you cannot complete the task alone, return what you have and escalate to the orchestrator.\n\n  Line 162: 3. **SET** `subagent_type: \"general\"` (all custom agents use the general subagent type)\n\n  Line 174: 3. `subagent_type: \"general\"` is only the runtime wrapper; it does not make a mismatched prompt safe.\n\n  Line 185: | @ai-council | `.opencode/agents/ai-council.md` | Planning-only multi-strategy architect (max 3 strategies). Post-dispatch responsibility: when @orchestrate dispatches at Depth 1, run `node .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/persist-artifacts.cjs <packet>` after the LEAF returns to persist `ai-council/` artifacts (see ai-council persistence protocol). |\n\n  Line 190: > **Note**: ALL exploration tasks route through `@context` exclusively. @context executes retrieval directly (no nested sub-agent dispatch).\n\n  Line 206: ├─ Agent: @code | @context | @markdown | @deep-context | @deep-research | @deep-review | @ai-council | @review | @debug\n\n  Line 435: **Action:** Mandate sub-agents to run `/memory:save` or `save context`.\n\n  Line 439: **Action:** ALWAYS dispatch `@context` (subagent_type: `\"general\"`). @context performs direct retrieval only and returns structured Context Packages.\n\n  Line 491: **Phase 1: UNDERSTANDING** — @context gathers context directly (no sub-agent fan-out)\n\n  Line 504: **NEVER accept sub-agent output blindly.** Every sub-agent response MUST be verified before synthesis.\n\n  Line 506: ### 🔒 Review Checklist (MANDATORY for every sub-agent response)\n\n  Line 585: 1. **RETRY (Attempts 1-2):** Provide additional context from other sub-agents, clarify success criteria, re-dispatch same agent with enhanced prompt. If still fails → REASSIGN.\n\n  Line 591: When a sub-agent returns \"Tool execution aborted\" or an empty/error result:\n\n  Line 633: After 3 failed attempts on the same error, prepare a diagnostic summary and prompt the user to dispatch `@debug` via Task tool. Never auto-dispatch — the user opts in. Auto-detect keywords for surfacing the prompt: \"stuck\", \"tried everything\", \"same error\", \"keeps failing\", or 3+ sub-agent dispatches returning errors.\n\n  Line 658: **Action:** Suggest `/memory:save` → mandate sub-agents save context → compile orchestration decisions summary → preserve task state, pending work, blockers.\n\n  Line 705: The orchestrator's context window is finite (~150K available tokens). When many sub-agents return large results simultaneously, the combined tokens cause irrecoverable errors. **The CWB constrains how results flow back.**\n\n  Line 794: | Agent definition          | ~15K tokens      | This orchestrate.md file                    |\n\n  Line 839: ❌ **Never let LEAF agents dispatch sub-agents**\n\n  Line 840: - LEAF agents (@context, @general, @markdown, @ai-council, @review, @debug, @deep-research, @deep-review) execute work directly. If a LEAF agent spawns a sub-agent, it violates NDP. When dispatching LEAF agents, ALWAYS include the LEAF Enforcement Instruction (§2).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/review.md:\n  Line 4: mode: subagent\n\n  Line 39: This agent is LEAF-only. Nested sub-agent dispatch is illegal.\n\n  Line 40: - NEVER create sub-tasks or dispatch sub-agents.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-click-up/README.md:\n  Line 161: This skill uses only the official `@clickup/mcp-server`. It never reaches for a community MCP server. The MCP transport and the `call_tool_chain()` invocation are owned by `mcp-code-mode`. This skill orchestrates the ClickUp surface. It does not implement the transport.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/codex_tools.md:\n  Line 105: codex exec \"Compare zod vs yup for TypeScript validation as of 2026. Search for benchmarks.\" \\\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/README.md:\n  Line 153: | `bash .opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh <runtime> [args]` | CLI | Launch an AI session in its own git worktree + branch + isolated MCP databases. Top-level sessions isolate; orchestrated children (`AI_SESSION_CHILD=1` or already inside a linked worktree) exec in place. `--dry-run` prints the plan. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/code.md:\n  Line 3: description: Application-code implementation specialist via sk-code. LEAF, dispatched only by @orchestrate.\n\n  Line 4: mode: subagent\n\n  Line 30: > ⛔ **DISPATCH GATE (§0 caller-restriction, D3 convention-floor):** @code MUST be dispatched by @orchestrate. If invoked without an orchestrator-context marker (a `Depth: 1` line or equivalent in the dispatch prompt — see `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md` §2 NDP), HALT and return:\n\n  Line 32: > \"REFUSE: @code is orchestrator-only. Dispatch via @orchestrate.\"\n\n  Line 46: This agent is LEAF-only. Nested sub-agent dispatch is illegal.\n\n  Line 47: - NEVER create sub-tasks or dispatch sub-agents.\n\n  Line 102: | **Excluded** | `sk-code-review` | Always excluded inside @code | Review-side only; @orchestrate dispatches @review separately |\n\n  Line 281: If @code returns `BLOCKED` three consecutive times for the same task id, @orchestrate should stop retrying @code and offer an `@debug` dispatch. The @debug prompt should include the latest @code RETURN blocks, gate validation results, verification commands, and partial findings.\n\n  Line 541: │  ├─► LEAF-only: no sub-agent dispatch or nested task creation           │\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/design.md:\n  Line 4: mode: subagent\n\n  Line 36: **Efficiency governor (the per-turn hook does not reach sub-agents -- apply it here)**:\n\n  Line 46: - NEVER dispatch sub-agents and NEVER use the Task/Agent tool.\n\n  Line 103: - Dispatch sub-agents or use the Task/Agent tool (LEAF-only).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/agent_delegation.md:\n  Line 29: Documents the active Codex agents in `.codex/agents/` and how any AI assistant orchestrates them. The calling AI acts as the **conductor** (planner, validator, integrator) while Codex CLI executes targeted tasks through its agent system.\n\n  Line 37: - Multi-agent Codex-side workflows (`@orchestrate`)\n\n  Line 120: [profiles.ai-council]\n\n  Line 199: ### @orchestrate — Task Commander\n\n  Line 206: | **Modifies Files** | Never (delegates to sub-agents)                 |\n\n  Line 212: **Note:** Avoid double-orchestration. If the calling AI is already decomposing tasks, delegate directly to leaf agents instead of routing through @orchestrate.\n\n  Line 215: codex exec -p orchestrate \\\n\n  Line 266: ### @ai-council — Multi-Strategy Planner\n\n  Line 280: codex exec -p ai-council -s read-only \\\n\n  Line 282:   --model gpt-5.5 > /tmp/ai-council-output.txt\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/deep-research.md:\n  Line 4: mode: subagent\n\n  Line 32: **Efficiency governor (the per-turn hook does not reach sub-agents — apply it here)**: reason about the problem, not yourself; lead with the result and act rather than narrate (batch tool calls, report at checkpoints); commit reversible decisions and move; qualify only when it changes what the reader should do.\n\n  Line 39: - **Leaf-only**: Never dispatch sub-agents and never use the Task tool.\n\n  Line 55: - `deep-ai-council` uses 0.20 default on adjudicator-verdict stability\n\n  Line 64: - NEVER create sub-tasks or dispatch sub-agents.\n\n  Line 306: - No sub-agent was dispatched.\n\n  Line 437: - Dispatch sub-agents or use Task tool (LEAF-only)\n\n  Line 529: [x] No sub-agents dispatched (LEAF compliance)\n\n  Line 579: │  ├─► LEAF-only: no sub-agent dispatch                                   │\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/SKILL.retired.md:\n  Line 107:     \"PATTERNS\":          {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"pattern\", \"workflow\", \"orchestrate\", \"session\", \"resume\", \"fork\"]},\n\n  Line 286: | Multi-strategy planning | ai-council | `codex exec -p ai-council \"Plan the authentication redesign\" -m gpt-5.5` |\n\n  Line 362: 10. **Never inject user-level voice/personalization content into AI-orchestrated Codex delegations.** Codex CLI reads user-level voice from `~/.codex/AGENTS.md` (the human's global settings, loaded automatically). When an AI delegates via `codex exec`, the calling AI's own voice rules govern the response — do NOT read `~/.codex/AGENTS.md` and paste into delegation prompts. Keep delegations focused on task/model/sandbox/effort/(spec-folder pre-approval). If the user asks how to make Codex sound more like Claude in *their own* sessions, point to `~/.codex/AGENTS.md` — not any repo asset.\n\n  Line 367: 15. **Set `AI_SESSION_CHILD=1` in the dispatched child's env** when sessions may be launched through the per-session worktree wrapper (`.opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh`). A dispatched `codex exec` is an orchestrated sub-session, not a new top-level session, so it must SHARE the parent's worktree rather than allocate its own. The wrapper checks `AI_SESSION_CHILD` (plus a `git --git-common-dir` structural backstop) and exec's in place when set. Pattern: `AI_SESSION_CHILD=1 codex exec ... </dev/null`. Harmless when the wrapper is not in use. See `.opencode/bin/README.md` → \"Worktree session isolation\".\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-sk-prompt-models-rename/004-commands-scripts-data/spec.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Update the workflow command YAMLs (deep_*.yaml benchmark/context paths), the pre-commit hook, the agent ref, and benchmark-output run-pointers to the new skill path.\"\n\n  Line 6:   - \"deep_model-benchmark benchmark path rename\"\n\n  Line 48: | **Handoff Criteria** | Command YAMLs + hook + agent + run-pointers point at the new path; benchmark/context workflows write/read the new location |\n\n  Line 56: This is **Phase 4** of the sk-prompt-models-rename specification — the workflow commands, scripts, agents, and benchmark-output pointers.\n\n  Line 58: **Scope Boundary**: `.opencode/commands/**`, `.opencode/scripts/**`, `.opencode/agents/**`, and run-pointers that name the benchmark output dir. The skill + sibling skills are phases 2–3; specs are phase 5.\n\n  Line 61: - Phase 2 (the benchmarks output dir now lives under `sk-prompt-models/benchmarks/`).\n\n  Line 64: - `commands/deep/assets/deep_model-benchmark_{auto,confirm}.yaml`: `benchmark_root`, `benchmark_report`, `reviewer_report`, the `mkdir`, the `loop-host --outputs-dir`, the `promote-candidate --benchmark-report` paths.\n\n  Line 66: - `commands/deep/model-benchmark.md`: the prose output-path mention.\n\n  Line 67: - `scripts/git-hooks/pre-commit`; the 1 `agents/` ref; benchmark run-pointers (e.g. `157-glm-5-2-support/002-framework-bakeoff/improvement/benchmark-run-pointer.json`).\n\n  Line 79: The `/deep:model-benchmark` and `/deep:context` workflows hardcode `.opencode/skills/sk-prompt-small-model/...` paths — the benchmark workflow writes outputs to and promotes from `sk-prompt-small-model/benchmarks/{run_label}`, and the context workflow loads `prompt_framing` from the SKILL.md. After the folder moves, those paths are dead.\n\n  Line 82: Repoint the command YAMLs, the pre-commit hook, the agent ref, and the benchmark run-pointers at `sk-prompt-models` so the deep-loop workflows write/read the correct location.\n\n  Line 91: - Token-replace in `commands/deep/assets/deep_model-benchmark_{auto,confirm}.yaml`, `deep_context_{auto,confirm}.yaml`, `commands/deep/model-benchmark.md`.\n\n  Line 92: - `scripts/git-hooks/pre-commit`, the `agents/` ref, and benchmark run-pointers under specs.\n\n  Line 101: | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_model-benchmark_{auto,confirm}.yaml` | Modify | benchmark_root/report/reviewer_report/mkdir/outputs-dir/promote paths |\n\n  Line 103: | `.opencode/commands/deep/model-benchmark.md` | Modify | prose output-path mention |\n\n  Line 106: | `…/157-glm-5-2-support/002-framework-bakeoff/improvement/benchmark-run-pointer.json` | Modify | `outputsDir` pointer into benchmarks/** |\n\n  Line 118: | REQ-001 | Benchmark workflow paths updated | All `sk-prompt-small-model/benchmarks/{run_label}` occurrences in the deep_model-benchmark YAMLs point at `sk-prompt-models/...` |\n\n  Line 140: - **Given** the edited deep_model-benchmark YAMLs, **When** a benchmark run is simulated, **Then** the output/promote paths resolve under `sk-prompt-models/benchmarks/`.\n\n  Line 150: | Risk | A YAML path occurrence missed | Benchmark writes to a dead path | rg the commands dir = 0 after edits; the count of benchmark paths is enumerated in phase 1 |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/cli_reference.md:\n  Line 400:     ├── orchestrate.toml\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"ai-council|orchestrate|sub-agent|subagent|Task\\(|subagent-only|subagent only|FIX-5|behavioral hardening|benchmark","time":{"start":1782887097255,"end":1782887097272}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_006772c5c80e4c32016a44b2b910a881919e0d49b0cc6ce114"}},"id":"prt_f1c5a2389001ugfq4K2BIjfbli","sessionID":"ses_0e3a7cbdbffepKwi4Ygk8sEv0I","messageID":"msg_f1c59aabe001oBPtl80yQRaH3F"}}
